Primitive Data Types:
Primitive datatypes include string, numbers, boolean, undefined and null.

• Number: Unlike other languages that separates the integers and decimals, JavaScript just has number for both.
let age = 28;
let price = 19.99;
• String: String holds the text which is enclosed in single quotes, double quotes, or backticks.
let name = "Alex";
let greeting = `Hello, ${name}!`; // "Hello, Alex!"
• Boolean: It acts as a true/false switch. Perfect for logic and conditional checks.
let isLoggedIn = true;
let hasPremiumAccount = false;
• Undefined: A variable that has been declared but no value has been assigned to it. Such variables give the output of undefined. It means the box exists, but it’s completely empty.
let bucket;
console.log(bucket); // undefined
• Null: This represents an intentional absence of value. It’s like putting an empty folder in your box.
let currentChampionshipWinner = null;
• Symbol: Generates a completely unique, immutable identifier often used as private keys for objects.
let id = Symbol("id");Non-Primitive Data Type:

• Object: A collection of key-value pairs used to represent complex structures.
let user = { name: "Bob", age: 30 };
• Array: An ordered list of values grouped together under a single variable.
let colors = ["red", "green", "blue"];
• Function: A callable block of code designed to perform a specific task.
function greet() {
return "Hello!";
}
